00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:19.530 --> 00:00:20.830
&gt;&gt; Larry R. Sarratt:
Good afternoon, everyone.

00:00:20.830 --> 00:00:25.200
It is indeed a great pleasure
to be here this afternoon.

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:27.160
My name is Larry R. Sarratt.

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:32.120
I'm the president of the Daniel
AP Murray African American

00:00:32.120 --> 00:00:35.000
Cultural Association of
the Library of Congress.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.830
I welcome you on behalf of our
first African-American Librarian

00:00:39.830 --> 00:00:41.970
of Congress Dr. Carla Hayden.

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:45.890
And we welcome you to the most
beautiful library in the world.

00:00:45.890 --> 00:00:51.050
The Daniel AP Murray Association
of the Library of Congress

00:00:51.050 --> 00:00:54.040
and the Motion Picture
Broadcasting

00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:58.190
and Recorded Sound Division of
the Library of Congress want

00:00:58.190 --> 00:01:00.930
to welcome you to an interview

00:01:00.930 --> 00:01:04.800
with the awesome
Russell Williams, II.

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:07.840
We welcome you and hope that
you will enjoy the interview.

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:09.640
Thank you.

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:19.490
[ Applause ]

00:01:19.490 --> 00:01:25.340
Now we will have the
highlight library collections.

00:01:25.340 --> 00:01:27.640
Will you all come at this time.

00:01:42.910 --> 00:01:44.230
&gt;&gt; Harrison Behl: Hi, everyone.

00:01:44.230 --> 00:01:46.420
Everybody can hear me okay?

00:01:46.420 --> 00:01:47.720
Okay great.

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:49.820
So, my name is Harrison Behl,
I'm a reference librarian

00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:51.530
in the Recorded Sound
Research Center

00:01:51.530 --> 00:01:54.400
in the Motion Picture Broadcast
and Recorded Sound Division.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:57.620
And we're very happy to be
cosponsoring this event today,

00:01:57.620 --> 00:02:00.200
and we're excited for
the interview as well.

00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:02.950
I thought I would just give you
an little bit of an overview

00:02:02.950 --> 00:02:05.290
of our collections, our history,

00:02:05.290 --> 00:02:08.330
and some of what we have
available in the recorded sound,

00:02:08.330 --> 00:02:10.240
and how it pertains to today.

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:14.300
The recorded sound collections
here at the library are born

00:02:14.300 --> 00:02:16.540
out of deposits that were made
to the library starting back

00:02:16.540 --> 00:02:21.030
in 1926 with early
78 RPM records.

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:24.330
At that time, recorded sound
was part of the music division,

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:27.390
and then in the seventies,
the record

00:02:27.390 --> 00:02:29.790
and sound session was
split out independently

00:02:29.790 --> 00:02:32.230
and the collections were
developed on their own.

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:36.510
Sound recordings weren't covered
under copyright until 1972.

00:02:36.510 --> 00:02:39.380
But once they were the library
started acquiring additional

00:02:39.380 --> 00:02:41.500
copies and our collections
really exploded.

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:42.990
So, since that time,
the library's so on.

00:02:42.990 --> 00:02:47.300
Since that time the library is
also been actively collecting

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:49.360
materials that were
produced before then to build

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:53.110
out a representative historical
collection on sound recordings.

00:02:53.110 --> 00:02:57.030
And currently we have about 3.5
million items in our holdings.

00:02:57.030 --> 00:02:59.550
They're all stored down
at Culpeper, Virginia,

00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:02.700
in the National Audiovisual
Conservation Center,

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:04.600
state-of-the-art
preservation facility

00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:08.010
with climate controlled,
you know, storage spaces

00:03:08.010 --> 00:03:11.730
and also dedicated preservation
staff and processing staff

00:03:11.730 --> 00:03:13.430
that take care of
the collections

00:03:13.430 --> 00:03:16.610
and make them accessible
to the public.

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:18.270
We do that in a couple
of different ways.

00:03:18.270 --> 00:03:21.470
There's dedicated preservation
going on all the time

00:03:21.470 --> 00:03:23.560
on large collections
that are prioritized

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:25.150
by our curatorial sections.

00:03:25.150 --> 00:03:28.070
That includes the
NBC radio collection,

00:03:28.070 --> 00:03:31.820
over 125,000 disks
we received from NBC,

00:03:31.820 --> 00:03:35.550
covering from the 1920s
up into the 1970s.

00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:37.150
And those are being
preserved all the time

00:03:37.150 --> 00:03:38.890
and more are being
made available.

00:03:38.890 --> 00:03:42.020
But our preservation is
also dictated by the request

00:03:42.020 --> 00:03:43.470
of our patrons and our users,

00:03:43.470 --> 00:03:45.790
who come into the Recorded
Sound Research Center,

00:03:45.790 --> 00:03:49.240
request materials and we can
get those digitized for them

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:51.580
on demand and access is
provided up here on the hill.

00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:52.960
So, we're the access point

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:55.080
for this huge collection
that's being taken care

00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:57.530
of down in Virginia.

00:03:57.530 --> 00:04:00.310
We have, as you see on the back
table here, we have a display

00:04:00.310 --> 00:04:03.150
of some of the formats that are
included in our collections.

00:04:03.150 --> 00:04:06.120
Over 120 years' worth
of ideas for how

00:04:06.120 --> 00:04:07.540
to capture sound recordings.

00:04:07.540 --> 00:04:10.230
From cylinders all the
way up to magnetic tapes,

00:04:10.230 --> 00:04:12.840
to the infamous 8-track,
and beyond.

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:14.700
So, take a look back there,

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:16.720
we're happy to answer
any questions about them.

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:19.520
And that's part of what makes
our collection so unique

00:04:19.520 --> 00:04:21.060
and challenging is
all the different ways

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:25.230
that we've you know recorded
material and made it available.

00:04:25.230 --> 00:04:28.140
I'm sure Mr. Russell's
career spans quite a few

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:29.440
of those different formats

00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:32.020
and quite a few challenges
have come up from that as well.

00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:36.410
A lot of your material is likely
represented in our collections

00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:38.440
through LP releases and
things like that too.

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:43.000
So, yeah, you're well taken
care of here, and with that,

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.410
I'll hand it over to my
colleague from Motion Picture.

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:49.480
&gt;&gt; Josie Walters-Johnston:
Hi, everybody,

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:51.990
my name is Josie
Walters-Johnston.

00:04:51.990 --> 00:04:56.020
I'm a reference librarian in the
Moving Image Research Center,

00:04:56.020 --> 00:04:59.470
which is the sister reading
room to Harrison's reading room.

00:04:59.470 --> 00:05:04.670
We are located in the
Madison Building in room 336,

00:05:04.670 --> 00:05:07.120
on the third floor,
right across from P&amp;P.

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:09.990
I just wanted to give you
a short introduction again,

00:05:09.990 --> 00:05:11.330
to what our reading room does.

00:05:11.330 --> 00:05:16.650
As Harrison explained, we are
split to the two reading rooms,

00:05:16.650 --> 00:05:21.110
and also the Packard Campus
down in Culpeper, Virginia.

00:05:21.110 --> 00:05:25.020
We have over 1.2 million
moving image items,

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:27.900
that cover all sorts of formats.

00:05:27.900 --> 00:05:31.850
And along with that, we
probably have another 2 million

00:05:31.850 --> 00:05:36.680
like paper documents to support
the research of that film

00:05:36.680 --> 00:05:37.980
and television material.

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:41.980
The items in our collections
expands the history of film

00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:43.830
and television industry.

00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:48.260
From Edison kinetoscopic record
of a sneeze, which was produced

00:05:48.260 --> 00:05:53.070
in 1894, to last season's
"Stranger Things."

00:05:53.070 --> 00:05:56.380
So, it's kind of like a
lot, a lot of material

00:05:56.380 --> 00:05:58.030
that we have in the collection.

00:05:58.030 --> 00:06:01.240
But we also have
feature films, newsreels,

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:05.010
educational industrial films,
television news, documentaries,

00:06:05.010 --> 00:06:09.390
reality TV program, TV
ads, and much, much more.

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:13.730
As Harrison said
in his statement,

00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:16.170
the majority the material that
we get in our collection is

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:17.470
through [inaudible] deposit.

00:06:17.470 --> 00:06:21.210
You want to register
material with us,

00:06:21.210 --> 00:06:22.730
you need to send us a copy.

00:06:22.730 --> 00:06:25.190
But then we also have things
like gift collections,

00:06:25.190 --> 00:06:29.270
and things that were
donated to us.

00:06:29.270 --> 00:06:33.350
NBC Television news
collection is a huge collection

00:06:33.350 --> 00:06:34.650
that we have.

00:06:34.650 --> 00:06:36.860
In the back, some of
the display items,

00:06:36.860 --> 00:06:40.480
it's actually the first episode
of a series called "Wide,

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:45.290
Wide World" from 1955,
I believe that was.

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:48.410
So, it's kind of an
ornamental cover.

00:06:48.410 --> 00:06:50.270
They didn't all come, all
the reels did not come

00:06:50.270 --> 00:06:53.710
in gold-plated kind of cover
things, but so we have things

00:06:53.710 --> 00:06:55.490
like that in our
collection as well.

00:06:55.490 --> 00:06:58.060
Another very large
collection is the NET,

00:06:58.060 --> 00:07:01.590
National Educational
Television, PBS collection.

00:07:01.590 --> 00:07:03.410
Huge collection.

00:07:03.410 --> 00:07:07.430
And actually, on that
note, in terms of material

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:11.370
that is accessible,
that collection is now,

00:07:11.370 --> 00:07:13.690
or parts of that
collection can be accessible

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:16.800
through the American
Archive of Public Television.

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:19.140
The cool thing about
that collection,

00:07:19.140 --> 00:07:20.700
you do not necessarily have

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:23.270
to physically be here
to get that material.

00:07:23.270 --> 00:07:25.450
You can log onto the
website from wherever

00:07:25.450 --> 00:07:28.010
and you can watch
PBS programming.

00:07:28.010 --> 00:07:30.600
Most of it is going to
probably focus more on,

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:33.660
like local PBS stations,
which is actually pretty cook,

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:36.510
but there are some of the
larger programs as well.

00:07:36.510 --> 00:07:39.280
Searching for materials
in our collection,

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:42.510
it means utilizing a bunch
of different resources.

00:07:42.510 --> 00:07:44.640
There's the Library of
Congress online catalog

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:47.660
of the MIRC Audiovisual
Information System, Mavis,

00:07:47.660 --> 00:07:50.190
which is an inhouse, we
still have a card catalog,

00:07:50.190 --> 00:07:52.200
we still love our card catalog.

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:55.120
And we also have finding aids.

00:07:55.120 --> 00:08:00.230
Without getting into a lot
of detail on how to do those,

00:08:00.230 --> 00:08:03.100
I'd might be happy, if you come
down and visit, give us a call,

00:08:03.100 --> 00:08:05.730
we can talk about how
to access that material,

00:08:05.730 --> 00:08:08.390
how best to utilize
the resources there.

00:08:08.390 --> 00:08:14.150
As I mentioned, the majority of
material is stored in Culpeper.

00:08:14.150 --> 00:08:17.590
So, most requests for
reviewing material needs

00:08:17.590 --> 00:08:18.890
to be made in advance.

00:08:18.890 --> 00:08:20.440
The only exception
to that is anything

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:22.640
that has already been digitized.

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:24.060
If something has been digitized,

00:08:24.060 --> 00:08:28.630
we can usually give
it to you on the spot.

00:08:28.630 --> 00:08:33.230
Unlike what your experience
might be in Recorded Sound,

00:08:33.230 --> 00:08:34.960
which is almost completely
digital,

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:37.270
when you come into listen.

00:08:37.270 --> 00:08:40.360
In the Moving Image Research
Center, you might be accessing

00:08:40.360 --> 00:08:42.790
like several different
formats on one day.

00:08:42.790 --> 00:08:46.220
So, you might have say, coming
in tomorrow, going to start

00:08:46.220 --> 00:08:49.070
with my 16-mm film, I'm going
to walk around to the other side

00:08:49.070 --> 00:08:51.410
of the viewing room,
going to watch some 35.

00:08:51.410 --> 00:08:53.230
Then, I'm going to go
to the other side again,

00:08:53.230 --> 00:08:54.870
and watch a laser disc.

00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:57.340
Maybe pop in Betamax,
watch a DVD.

00:08:57.340 --> 00:09:00.300
Maybe a three-quarter
inch pneumatic tape

00:09:00.300 --> 00:09:03.250
and then end my day
watching digital material.

00:09:03.250 --> 00:09:07.310
So, we cover all of
those different formats.

00:09:07.310 --> 00:09:10.230
And then, in addition to
the moving image themselves,

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:12.870
we also have paper material.

00:09:12.870 --> 00:09:16.950
So, we have periodicals,
reference books, subject files,

00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:20.270
screenplays, transcripts,
photographs, lobby cards,

00:09:20.270 --> 00:09:22.920
press kits, pretty much anything

00:09:22.920 --> 00:09:26.880
that will help supplement your
film or television research.

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:30.840
In the back, just to point
out a couple of the examples

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:32.710
and material that
are back there.

00:09:32.710 --> 00:09:35.360
The first thing you'll see
is actually a press kit

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:36.660
from "Field of Dreams."

00:09:36.660 --> 00:09:39.300
It's actually the press kit and
production notes are inside.

00:09:39.300 --> 00:09:43.340
And I already mentioned
there's the NBC TV collection,

00:09:43.340 --> 00:09:46.220
the "Wide, Wide World"
premiere episode.

00:09:46.220 --> 00:09:49.850
And then, items 3
and 4 are essentially

00:09:49.850 --> 00:09:51.150
from the same collection.

00:09:51.150 --> 00:09:52.450
Our earliest collection.

00:09:52.450 --> 00:09:54.960
It's called the paper
print collection.

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:57.350
That's a portion of it
called the paper print

00:09:57.350 --> 00:09:58.650
fragment collection.

00:09:58.650 --> 00:10:01.930
So, this is material that was
received before there was a way

00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:04.040
to register your
films for copyright.

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:08.870
So, this would be
anything before 1912.

00:10:08.870 --> 00:10:10.580
So, those are back
there as well.

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:13.620
And then, on the side,
we both have handouts

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:15.470
that you can take with you.

00:10:15.470 --> 00:10:17.900
There is just pamphlet
information

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:19.200
about both reading rooms.

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:22.520
There's how to search, we
have viewing guidelines,

