00:18:45.410 --> 00:18:47.520
to Nevada this afternoon,
she just wanted to come here

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:49.680
and bring the family love.

00:18:49.680 --> 00:18:53.260
I have other family members
here, but Southeast that we grew

00:18:53.260 --> 00:18:57.240
up in was a very
tightknit community.

00:18:57.240 --> 00:18:59.470
It's not the Southeast
that you typically see

00:18:59.470 --> 00:19:00.770
on television today.

00:19:00.770 --> 00:19:03.150
Generally, it's bad
news if Southeast shows

00:19:03.150 --> 00:19:08.810
up on TV these days and it's
a really unfair portrayal.

00:19:08.810 --> 00:19:14.010
Everybody knew everybody
else's kids, Luis, everybody,

00:19:14.010 --> 00:19:16.990
all the kids knew
everybody else's parents.

00:19:16.990 --> 00:19:20.330
So, just because you went around
the corner and broke a bottle,

00:19:20.330 --> 00:19:24.470
or maybe, you know threw a
piece of paper in the middle

00:19:24.470 --> 00:19:27.280
of the street, or something
in someone's yard and ran

00:19:27.280 --> 00:19:28.910
around the corner assuming

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:30.940
that you had gotten
away with something.

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:35.430
I'm sorry old ma Bell, on
those rotary telephones,

00:19:35.430 --> 00:19:39.090
you young people Google
that see what it looks like.

00:19:39.090 --> 00:19:41.110
You know, there's no
digital devices back then,

00:19:41.110 --> 00:19:42.410
just Google it.

00:19:42.410 --> 00:19:44.590
And mom or dad or
somebody would be standing

00:19:44.590 --> 00:19:47.500
out on the porch waiting
for you to get back.

00:19:47.500 --> 00:19:49.730
Were you at Mr. Clavell's place
and did you break a bottle

00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:51.540
in front of his house,
and you know.

00:19:51.540 --> 00:19:56.050
So, we knew that
all eyes were on us.

00:19:56.050 --> 00:19:59.930
We also knew that
you were penalized

00:19:59.930 --> 00:20:02.430
if you disrespected your
elders, you were penalized

00:20:02.430 --> 00:20:06.040
if you disrespected
other people's property.

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:09.540
We were also taught that
regardless of one's station

00:20:09.540 --> 00:20:13.490
in life from an economic
standpoint, a job, or title,

00:20:13.490 --> 00:20:15.540
you had to respect everybody.

00:20:15.540 --> 00:20:20.110
And everyone could take a piece
of you if you step out of line.

00:20:20.110 --> 00:20:22.550
That's at church,
that's at school.

00:20:22.550 --> 00:20:23.850
You know what I'm saying,

00:20:23.850 --> 00:20:25.150
that's one of the
neighbors up the street.

00:20:25.150 --> 00:20:31.840
I remember distinctly, I think
second grade, I hit somebody

00:20:31.840 --> 00:20:35.260
with a spitball, first
thing in the morning.

00:20:35.260 --> 00:20:38.570
Okay, boom, teacher
took me out by the hand,

00:20:38.570 --> 00:20:40.560
making sure that I
felt pain on the way

00:20:40.560 --> 00:20:42.880
to the assistant
principal's office,

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:46.160
this was at Davis
Elementary School, by the way.

00:20:46.160 --> 00:20:48.160
Then the assistant
principal took a piece of me,

00:20:48.160 --> 00:20:50.770
and then they did the most
horrible thing I could imagine,

00:20:50.770 --> 00:20:53.800
they called my mother at home.

00:20:53.800 --> 00:20:57.250
And mother, who at that time
wasn't driving had to walk

00:20:57.250 --> 00:21:01.640
to school to get her
recalcitrant son.

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:05.390
Walk me back, tuning
me up all the way.

00:21:05.390 --> 00:21:07.550
So, that was probably
10;30 in the morning,

00:21:07.550 --> 00:21:11.030
so I'm thinking okay I'm done,
right, but here comes about 5:30

00:21:11.030 --> 00:21:12.330
or 6, here comes my dad.

00:21:12.330 --> 00:21:14.440
And it starts all over again.

00:21:14.440 --> 00:21:17.530
I only had one job to do,
that was to get As and Bs,

00:21:17.530 --> 00:21:20.400
and if I'm in school
clowning and being disruptive,

00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:25.090
that's not the son that he
and his wife wanted to raise.

00:21:25.090 --> 00:21:28.130
And even as a high
school student at Wilson,

00:21:28.130 --> 00:21:30.020
if I'm standing at the
bus stop on Benning Road,

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:34.930
my old Davis principal would
roll by and say, "Williams,

00:21:34.930 --> 00:21:36.760
are you still getting
As and Bs, have you been

00:21:36.760 --> 00:21:38.060
in any kind of trouble?

00:21:38.060 --> 00:21:39.360
I'm going to check on you.

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:40.660
I'm going to check with
your dad, to make sure."

00:21:40.660 --> 00:21:42.070
I mean this seemed like
a lifelong connection,

00:21:42.070 --> 00:21:44.000
that was the southeast
that we grew up in.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:47.000
The people I pointed out and I'm
sure others that are in here.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:48.500
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: Yeah, well
we'd really like to get some

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:50.430
of those qualities back
into the community.

00:21:50.430 --> 00:21:52.150
and part of the value
of speaking

00:21:52.150 --> 00:21:54.890
with you today is
having a master's class

00:21:54.890 --> 00:21:56.440
with a master teacher.

00:21:56.440 --> 00:21:59.430
And I think that as we listen,
the young people and people

00:21:59.430 --> 00:22:02.170
with children in the
audience, as well as people

00:22:02.170 --> 00:22:05.060
that are your age can
reflect on the experience.

00:22:05.060 --> 00:22:06.910
Maybe we can get
back to some of that.

00:22:06.910 --> 00:22:10.880
Let's talk about say,
high school and Wilson.

00:22:10.880 --> 00:22:14.640
I know that you played band
and were talking about sound.

00:22:14.640 --> 00:22:18.190
Sound design and a
great within that genre,

00:22:18.190 --> 00:22:22.480
so was Bennett Wilson
the first area of sound

00:22:22.480 --> 00:22:24.290
that you entered into?

00:22:24.290 --> 00:22:27.190
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II: Well I
will have to go back a few years

00:22:27.190 --> 00:22:29.790
when I was actually
about 10 years old.

00:22:29.790 --> 00:22:32.810
I was attending a church in
Northwest with my parents

00:22:32.810 --> 00:22:35.350
and for some reason
I want to say

00:22:35.350 --> 00:22:38.190
of the choir was
singing spiritual,

00:22:38.190 --> 00:22:42.970
the title is 'Hear a Voice a
Praying,' and it was acapella.

00:22:42.970 --> 00:22:45.460
And they were in
good form that day.

00:22:45.460 --> 00:22:48.710
And I got a little misty
eyed, and some of the elders

00:22:48.710 --> 00:22:51.430
who saw me in the
congregation ran to my mom

00:22:51.430 --> 00:22:56.110
and said I think Russell's been
called to preach [laughter].

00:22:58.190 --> 00:23:02.320
No, but I do want to
take piano lessons.

00:23:02.320 --> 00:23:05.550
So, about 10 years old, I
started taking piano and one

00:23:05.550 --> 00:23:08.860
of the pictures that's
going by is me standing

00:23:08.860 --> 00:23:12.220
between two ladies, one of
those ladies was my first piano

00:23:12.220 --> 00:23:14.130
teacher Claretta Proctor.

00:23:14.130 --> 00:23:15.940
And that's also a shot
of me right on there now

00:23:15.940 --> 00:23:18.560
at a recital that just passed.

00:23:18.560 --> 00:23:21.180
So, playing piano
was the first thing

00:23:21.180 --> 00:23:23.770
that really made me
a critical listener.

00:23:23.770 --> 00:23:27.410
Playing piano also was the
first time that I realized,

00:23:27.410 --> 00:23:32.500
I'd heard this whole story about
music can calm the savage beast,

00:23:32.500 --> 00:23:35.260
but you know that's stuff
that old folks say to you,

00:23:35.260 --> 00:23:36.560
it doesn't really mean anything,

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:38.150
they're just saying
that stuff to you.

00:23:38.150 --> 00:23:40.360
Just to get your
out of their face.

00:23:40.360 --> 00:23:42.180
So, for some reason, I
can't remember what it was,

00:23:42.180 --> 00:23:44.780
I was very upset with my mom
one day, and I said okay,

00:23:44.780 --> 00:23:46.200
and she was watching
her soap operas.

00:23:46.200 --> 00:23:48.650
I said, I'm going to ruin her
day, I'm going to go downstairs

00:23:48.650 --> 00:23:51.360
and start banging on the
piano, so loud that it's going

00:23:51.360 --> 00:23:54.020
to interrupt her watching
the soap opera, right?

00:23:54.020 --> 00:23:56.950
And I kind of wore myself
out doing that and I said,

00:23:56.950 --> 00:23:58.700
well I'm down here, I
might as well do my lesson,

00:23:58.700 --> 00:24:00.930
which wasn't anything really
complicated at that point it was

00:24:00.930 --> 00:24:03.340
like de, da, de, da, de,
da, de; na, na, de, da, de.

00:24:03.340 --> 00:24:06.500
You know it wasn't anything
like Rachmaninoff of Bach

00:24:06.500 --> 00:24:09.460
or anything, but literally about
three or four minutes later,

00:24:09.460 --> 00:24:11.900
I couldn't remember
what I was angry about.

00:24:11.900 --> 00:24:16.710
And so that was the first
time I realized how music can

00:24:16.710 --> 00:24:19.010
transport you.

00:24:19.010 --> 00:24:23.240
I would blame the 1959
"Ben-Hur," which I saw

00:24:23.240 --> 00:24:26.090
as a 7-year-old for
really showing me the power

00:24:26.090 --> 00:24:28.100
of music in film.

00:24:28.100 --> 00:24:30.470
Because I know I was sitting
next to my parents, and I said,

00:24:30.470 --> 00:24:31.830
I don't know what this
movie is going to be about,

00:24:31.830 --> 00:24:33.670
but it sounds very important.

00:24:33.670 --> 00:24:36.310
But, you know 10 years old
was when I could put my hands

00:24:36.310 --> 00:24:38.100
on an instrument
for the first time.

00:24:38.100 --> 00:24:42.150
So, that led to going to Wilson
by my Piano teacher's suggesting

00:24:42.150 --> 00:24:44.740
to get onto an orchestral
instrument

00:24:44.740 --> 00:24:46.400
as well as playing piano.

00:24:46.400 --> 00:24:49.560
That's when I really developed
an appreciation for rangers

00:24:49.560 --> 00:24:51.680
and composers and
things like that.

00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:54.720
And as far as I was concerned,
I was going to be a music major.

00:24:54.720 --> 00:25:00.640
And then my master pianist
made the mistake of telling me

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:04.340
about some of his co-eds at
Peabody Conservatory, a couple,

00:25:04.340 --> 00:25:06.610
three had jumped out of a window

00:25:06.610 --> 00:25:08.230
because they had
failed the final exam.

00:25:08.230 --> 00:25:09.630
I said, you know what?

00:25:09.630 --> 00:25:11.310
Maybe not, maybe not.

00:25:11.310 --> 00:25:13.610
You know, I want to
keep my love as music

00:25:13.610 --> 00:25:16.490
as something that's no
pressure involved, you know.

00:25:16.490 --> 00:25:19.170
And so, that's when I kind of
started thinking about something

00:25:19.170 --> 00:25:22.210
in the communications field by
the time I got to American U.

00:25:22.210 --> 00:25:23.510
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: Well,
that's interesting,

00:25:23.510 --> 00:25:25.620
I can see the less
dangerous approach.

00:25:25.620 --> 00:25:29.350
But then, after the piano, I
think you picked up the tuba,

00:25:29.350 --> 00:25:32.060
which seems like a dangerous
instrument, back again.

00:25:32.060 --> 00:25:33.360
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II: Well,

00:25:33.360 --> 00:25:34.660
it was dangerous riding
on the Maryland bus.

00:25:34.660 --> 00:25:37.690
You all remember the WMA
bus, now that's real DC folks

00:25:37.690 --> 00:25:39.330
if you can remember DC Transit.

00:25:39.330 --> 00:25:41.440
But then on the other side
of town was this orange kind

00:25:41.440 --> 00:25:45.010
of brownish bus called
WMA, which was kind

00:25:45.010 --> 00:25:47.890
of like the second
cousin from a bad marriage

00:25:47.890 --> 00:25:50.410
in terms of transit systems.

00:25:50.410 --> 00:25:53.580
And by that time, I was
at Kramer Junior High,

00:25:53.580 --> 00:25:56.730
and Ms. Lockhart, who
was our band director,

00:25:56.730 --> 00:25:58.460
orchestra director actually.

00:25:58.460 --> 00:26:00.140
Said, oh I'm so happy
that you want to pick

00:26:00.140 --> 00:26:01.810
up another instrument,
and she had this room full

00:26:01.810 --> 00:26:03.830
of instruments that
nobody was playing

00:26:03.830 --> 00:26:05.940
and so she was suggesting
maybe a clarinet,

00:26:05.940 --> 00:26:07.620
or maybe a violin or something.

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:08.920
And I'm thinking,
no I don't want

00:26:08.920 --> 00:26:10.990
to take another hard instrument.

00:26:10.990 --> 00:26:13.370
And is said what's that orphan
in the corner over there.

00:26:13.370 --> 00:26:14.670
It was a tuba.

00:26:14.670 --> 00:26:17.880
It was kind of bent up, and
it needed some Brasso on it.

00:26:17.880 --> 00:26:19.180
So, she said, oh that'd be great

00:26:19.180 --> 00:26:20.480
because I don't really
have anybody playing

00:26:20.480 --> 00:26:22.050
in the low register.

00:26:22.050 --> 00:26:25.020
And I knew already, I could
pick up the tuba parts probably

00:26:25.020 --> 00:26:28.200
by Monday, and just sound
the note on the piano,

00:26:28.200 --> 00:26:29.590
find it on the tuba,
and you know,

00:26:29.590 --> 00:26:31.360
I could already read music.

00:26:31.360 --> 00:26:32.680
So, that was a done deal.

00:26:32.680 --> 00:26:36.520
Right, except I said okay so
where's the case [laughter].

00:26:37.690 --> 00:26:40.190
Oh, there is no case.

00:26:40.190 --> 00:26:47.540
Okay, so here's pudgy
Russell on the bus with a tuba

00:26:47.540 --> 00:26:52.570
and so you all can go on and
figure out the comedy routines

00:26:52.570 --> 00:26:56.560
that spawn from those
trips back and forth.

00:26:56.560 --> 00:27:00.110
But anyway, you know, I
weather that as a lot of other,

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:02.180
you know, banter
in southeast, DC.

00:27:02.180 --> 00:27:05.470
I mean I think growing up in
southeast made it really easy

00:27:05.470 --> 00:27:08.160
to merge into professional
work was when people think

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:10.270
that they've cut you,
they've insulted you,

00:27:10.270 --> 00:27:11.980
they said something
that was going

00:27:11.980 --> 00:27:13.400
to you know get you
off of your mark.

00:27:13.400 --> 00:27:16.350
And I'm like, no, you got to,
you need to go to grad school.

00:27:16.350 --> 00:27:18.530
You go to middle
school in southeast,

00:27:18.530 --> 00:27:20.020
then you can learn
how to insult people.

00:27:20.020 --> 00:27:24.010
This isn't even an
inconvenience, you know.

00:27:24.010 --> 00:27:26.000
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell:
I see your point.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:30.150
I also remember you talking
about your dad, and the lessons

00:27:30.150 --> 00:27:31.560
that you learned from him.

00:27:31.560 --> 00:27:33.940
I would imagine at that
time, when you're going

00:27:33.940 --> 00:27:35.490
through high school
your relationship

00:27:35.490 --> 00:27:37.050
with him was very connected.

00:27:37.050 --> 00:27:41.360
Can you talk a little bit
about what he did and what kind

00:27:41.360 --> 00:27:42.890
of influence he had on you

00:27:42.890 --> 00:27:44.190
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II: Well,

00:27:44.190 --> 00:27:46.740
you know I'm probably
not unusual in this room,

00:27:46.740 --> 00:27:54.430
especially at with my tender
age 30 times 2, plus 5.

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:55.730
Yeah, yeah.

00:27:55.730 --> 00:27:58.750
Now, y'all don't rush me.

00:27:58.750 --> 00:28:00.340
I'll get there, but
I'm not there yet.

00:28:00.340 --> 00:28:03.310
So, I actually, I had two dads.

00:28:03.310 --> 00:28:05.940
So, I had Russell
Williams, senior.

00:28:05.940 --> 00:28:10.380
And unfortunately, I'd lost
my birth mother the day

00:28:10.380 --> 00:28:12.170
after I was born.

00:28:12.170 --> 00:28:17.630
So, standing there in the
emergency room was James Harshaw

00:28:17.630 --> 00:28:21.480
and my mother's next
oldest sister, Ruth.

00:28:21.480 --> 00:28:24.520
And they were childless, and
they made the commitment right

00:28:24.520 --> 00:28:26.860
at that moment to say, you
know, we'll raise your son.

00:28:26.860 --> 00:28:29.000
Because Russell Williams
is working the night shift

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.190
at Union Station as a reg cap.

00:28:32.190 --> 00:28:35.690
So, basically, it was tag team.

00:28:35.690 --> 00:28:37.770
He was a Taurus, Russell
Williams the first,

00:28:37.770 --> 00:28:41.260
James Harshaw was a Taurus, and
I want to say Ruth was a Taurus.

00:28:41.260 --> 00:28:44.770
It was actually you know I was
getting it three different ways.

00:28:44.770 --> 00:28:47.620
So, James Harshaw was
a master carpenter,

00:28:47.620 --> 00:28:50.100
he worked at the
government printing office.

00:28:50.100 --> 00:28:52.030
And he also, you know,

00:28:52.030 --> 00:28:54.850
like pretty much any other
African American male

00:28:54.850 --> 00:28:58.460
or female back then, they had
two or three other side jobs.

00:28:58.460 --> 00:29:01.040
He drove a cab, you
know on days off.

00:29:01.040 --> 00:29:03.820
He also, because of
being a master carpenter,

00:29:03.820 --> 00:29:06.190
he would get together with other
buddies, a next-door neighbor

00:29:06.190 --> 00:29:09.190
who couldn't be here today,
her husband was a painter

00:29:09.190 --> 00:29:11.530
and down the street
we had a mason,

00:29:11.530 --> 00:29:14.880
and around the corner we had
someone who did electrical work.

00:29:14.880 --> 00:29:17.260
And they did a lot of
recreational rooms.

00:29:17.260 --> 00:29:20.560
You remember those, the you
know the knotty pine walls,

00:29:20.560 --> 00:29:23.090
and the drop ceilings
and all of that.

00:29:23.090 --> 00:29:25.720
And you know, I'm sawing
wood and doing this kind

00:29:25.720 --> 00:29:27.790
of stuff saying, I'm never
going to be a carpenter,

00:29:27.790 --> 00:29:29.090
[inaudible] carpenter job.

00:29:29.090 --> 00:29:31.560
But, you know, I
learned the trade.

00:29:31.560 --> 00:29:33.600
I learned how important
it was to be precise.

00:29:33.600 --> 00:29:36.120
I learned how important
it was to make sure

00:29:36.120 --> 00:29:38.420
that the customer satisfied.

00:29:38.420 --> 00:29:42.260
So, that was that was one of
the lessons from James Harshaw.

00:29:42.260 --> 00:29:43.570
And I use that lesson

00:29:43.570 --> 00:29:46.790
about learning a trade
later on in life.

00:29:46.790 --> 00:29:51.320
Russell Williams, senior
he loved the blues.

00:29:51.320 --> 00:29:54.140
His motto or his saying,

00:29:54.140 --> 00:29:57.280
regardless of when all the
other voices, my half-sisters

00:29:57.280 --> 00:29:59.370
and everybody were
in the room partying,

00:29:59.370 --> 00:30:02.550
and discussing the pros
and cons of this, that,

00:30:02.550 --> 00:30:04.910
and music artists of this style.

00:30:04.910 --> 00:30:06.370
And they would get
all up in arms.

00:30:06.370 --> 00:30:09.390
He'd say, look, he said
don't sweat the small stuff.

00:30:09.390 --> 00:30:11.610
And so that was, you would
hear him say at least two

00:30:11.610 --> 00:30:13.610
or three times a visit,
don't sweat the small stuff.

00:30:13.610 --> 00:30:15.310
He was only focused
on the big picture.

00:30:15.310 --> 00:30:19.620
So, there weren't too
many folks I could go

00:30:19.620 --> 00:30:22.060
to to have a pity party.

00:30:22.060 --> 00:30:25.740
You know, Mr. Harshaw would say,
well, you know that's a problem.

00:30:25.740 --> 00:30:27.710
But you know what half the
people are glad you have

00:30:27.710 --> 00:30:29.040
problems, the other
half don't care,

00:30:29.040 --> 00:30:31.390
so which group are you
going to complain to.

00:30:31.390 --> 00:30:32.690
That was his way of saying,

00:30:32.690 --> 00:30:33.990
you have to work
this out on your own.

00:30:33.990 --> 00:30:35.290
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: Fantastic.

00:30:35.290 --> 00:30:36.590
I want to get back
to some of the things

00:30:36.590 --> 00:30:39.190
that Mr. Harshaw told you
before you went to NBC.

00:30:39.190 --> 00:30:41.360
Because I think that's
fantastic.

00:30:41.360 --> 00:30:43.290
But I think this is
a good point to start

00:30:43.290 --> 00:30:44.590
to talk about the library.

00:30:44.590 --> 00:30:45.890
Is that okay?

00:30:45.890 --> 00:30:47.190
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams,
II: Absolutely.

00:30:47.190 --> 00:30:48.680
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: All right,
well Professor Williams,

00:30:48.680 --> 00:30:51.170
you've been an employee
of the library before.

00:30:51.170 --> 00:30:54.290
Could you describe that
experience a little for us.

00:30:54.290 --> 00:30:55.630
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II:
There's a gentleman who is not

00:30:55.630 --> 00:30:58.840
with us today, meaning he's
still on the planet but not

00:30:58.840 --> 00:31:02.340
in the room today,
Lowell Vincent Muse.

00:31:02.340 --> 00:31:05.570
He was also part of the spirits
known and unknown workshop.

00:31:05.570 --> 00:31:10.370
And he was working part-time
here at the Library of Congress.

00:31:10.370 --> 00:31:14.140
By this time I was an undergrad
at American U. And he mentioned,

00:31:14.140 --> 00:31:17.730
hey, you know, the LOC has these
part-time gigs, I think it was 4

00:31:17.730 --> 00:31:21.370
to 8:15 or 8:30, every
day, 5 days a week.

00:31:21.370 --> 00:31:23.870
So, you could get your classes
out of the way, come down here

00:31:23.870 --> 00:31:26.960
and make some good old
government money, right.

00:31:26.960 --> 00:31:29.540
And in my parents'
generation coming

00:31:29.540 --> 00:31:33.980
from the Carolinas you know
you had reached the mountaintop

00:31:33.980 --> 00:31:37.720
when you have a federal
government job.

00:31:37.720 --> 00:31:41.260
All right, you could
basically relax.

00:31:41.260 --> 00:31:45.750
And just know that you put your
kids in college, you could buy

00:31:45.750 --> 00:31:50.030
that boat that you wanted, or
you know, buy a vacation home

00:31:50.030 --> 00:31:52.590
or something, or whatever
you wanted to do it right.

00:31:52.590 --> 00:31:54.310
So, I said, great.

00:31:54.310 --> 00:31:58.670
I applied for the job, it was in
the stack and reader division,

00:31:58.670 --> 00:32:00.210
does that still exist?

00:32:00.210 --> 00:32:03.850
No stack and reader anymore?

00:32:03.850 --> 00:32:08.440
Okay, all right, but you
know what I'm talking about.

00:32:08.440 --> 00:32:11.180
I was handling the PZs.

00:32:11.180 --> 00:32:14.200
A lot of the literature
books, right, okay.

00:32:14.200 --> 00:32:18.650
Yes, and running over to their
conveyor belt to put, you know,

00:32:18.650 --> 00:32:21.370
books down that would
end up in main control.

00:32:21.370 --> 00:32:25.320
And as would happen as you
were going down the corridors

00:32:25.320 --> 00:32:26.780
of the Jefferson Building
every now and then,

00:32:26.780 --> 00:32:29.940
I'd look up at the job
board, and I saw this job

00:32:29.940 --> 00:32:32.570
from what was then
called the music division.

00:32:32.570 --> 00:32:35.870
And it talked about, well
first of all you need

00:32:35.870 --> 00:32:38.770
to understand professional
audio gear, I'm like well yeah,

00:32:38.770 --> 00:32:41.620
I'm on the radio,
so that's a start.

00:32:41.620 --> 00:32:44.230
A quarter inch tape
recording, yeah I can do that.

00:32:44.230 --> 00:32:46.470
Equalization, so on,
and so on, and so on.

00:32:46.470 --> 00:32:48.510
And this would be a
fulltime job, you know,

00:32:48.510 --> 00:32:51.440
in the preservation of
old materials like you see

00:32:51.440 --> 00:32:53.140
in the back of the room.

00:32:53.140 --> 00:32:56.780
In our era we were working
with the 16-inch planners from

00:32:56.780 --> 00:32:58.300
"Major Bowes Amateur Hour."

00:32:58.300 --> 00:33:00.860
I know you've read about
it, but none of the people

00:33:00.860 --> 00:33:03.560
in this room have
actually heard Major Bowes,

00:33:03.560 --> 00:33:05.740
I mean nobody's that old.

00:33:05.740 --> 00:33:07.110
But you can hear
recordings of it,

00:33:07.110 --> 00:33:10.070
that's what I was
doing at first at LOC.

00:33:10.070 --> 00:33:15.710
And that lasted until
probably the spring of 1973,

00:33:15.710 --> 00:33:19.880
when the opportunity to
take a temporary sink

00:33:19.880 --> 00:33:22.930
or swim job at Channel
4 came up.

00:33:22.930 --> 00:33:26.300
TV engineers are what they
call summer relief engineer.

00:33:26.300 --> 00:33:30.620
So, you were working for union
scale, and you would be working

00:33:30.620 --> 00:33:34.010
on whatever WRC, NBC
was putting on the air,

00:33:34.010 --> 00:33:36.060
but the caveat was
you got a chance

00:33:36.060 --> 00:33:39.660
to make three on-air mistakes.

00:33:39.660 --> 00:33:42.520
That third mistake ends up
on air, you are a memory.

00:33:42.520 --> 00:33:44.930
That means see you,
bye, nothing person.

00:33:44.930 --> 00:33:48.330
So, I gave up one delivery.

00:33:48.330 --> 00:33:52.710
The second one actually was
because I had trusted Pepco

00:33:52.710 --> 00:33:56.820
to keep power on all night,
even during a thunderstorm,

00:33:56.820 --> 00:33:58.510
of course, that didn't happen.

00:33:58.510 --> 00:34:00.600
So, I was late for
work one time.

00:34:00.600 --> 00:34:02.220
I never had that problem again.

00:34:02.220 --> 00:34:04.500
And so, I got through
the rest of my summer

00:34:04.500 --> 00:34:06.070
without getting to that third.

00:34:06.070 --> 00:34:11.930
They had a term for it,
the initials were DS.

00:34:11.930 --> 00:34:14.900
So, I got out of there
without that third DS.

00:34:14.900 --> 00:34:17.460
But my parents are
very disappointed in me

00:34:17.460 --> 00:34:20.410
because I was leaving a
could of been permanent job

00:34:20.410 --> 00:34:24.720
for the federal government, to
take a chance on a temporary job

00:34:24.720 --> 00:34:26.500
in this crazy TV business.

00:34:26.500 --> 00:34:31.790
And I said well, as politely as
I could, I said well understand,

00:34:31.790 --> 00:34:35.710
you guys came up from the
cotton fields, one of the things

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:38.800
that you did by coming up from
the cotton fields was give me

00:34:38.800 --> 00:34:41.560
the honor of not having to
pick cotton at all except off

00:34:41.560 --> 00:34:44.590
of a hanger in the closet.

00:34:44.590 --> 00:34:46.950
Also, you've all
given me a platform

00:34:46.950 --> 00:34:49.540
that I can hopefully
write my own ticket,

00:34:49.540 --> 00:34:52.830
as opposed to just following
completely in your footsteps,

00:34:52.830 --> 00:34:55.670
so I said that's what my
mission is is to go further

00:34:55.670 --> 00:34:56.970
than you've allowed me to go,

00:34:56.970 --> 00:34:58.910
and further than you all
could go in your era,

00:34:58.910 --> 00:35:00.810
I've got to push it further.

00:35:00.810 --> 00:35:06.770
So, I took the job at NBC, and
that was a successful summer,

00:35:06.770 --> 00:35:08.950
but it showed me that I could
make it in show business

00:35:08.950 --> 00:35:12.310
and that sounds like a
kind of egotistical remark.

00:35:12.310 --> 00:35:15.030
But there was this little thing
called the Watergate Hearings

00:35:15.030 --> 00:35:19.560
that was going on in the summer
of '73, and I worked along

00:35:19.560 --> 00:35:21.230
with a lot of the other
crew people there,

00:35:21.230 --> 00:35:26.180
we worked 22-hour
days 5 days a week.

00:35:26.180 --> 00:35:28.340
All right?

00:35:28.340 --> 00:35:30.310
So, that means you would
bring some clothes in with you

00:35:30.310 --> 00:35:31.850
on Monday and a bar of soap.

00:35:31.850 --> 00:35:34.990
You would sleep on a bench
between midnight and 2 a.m.

00:35:34.990 --> 00:35:37.620
and 2 a.m. you were
back on the stage,

00:35:37.620 --> 00:35:39.510
lighting "The Today Show."

00:35:39.510 --> 00:35:41.590
That's when I knew, okay I
can put up with the hours,

00:35:41.590 --> 00:35:43.170
I can put up with
live television,

00:35:43.170 --> 00:35:45.620
because if you make
a mistake on live TV,

00:35:45.620 --> 00:35:47.290
there is no bringing it back.

00:35:47.290 --> 00:35:52.950
That era was Barbara Walters as
the cohost of "The Today Show."

00:35:52.950 --> 00:35:54.800
And Frank McGee was
the other person.

00:35:54.800 --> 00:35:57.140
John Chancellor was
the nightly news guy.

00:35:57.140 --> 00:35:58.510
So, that was the era.

00:35:58.510 --> 00:36:00.310
And I still had one
year at American U

00:36:00.310 --> 00:36:02.830
to finish, but I was like, okay.

00:36:02.830 --> 00:36:05.930
As far as I was concerned, it
was going to be broadcast TV.

00:36:05.930 --> 00:36:09.270
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: Fascinating,
and let's talk more about NBC

00:36:09.270 --> 00:36:10.640
and Watergate, because I think

00:36:10.640 --> 00:36:12.720
that that's a very
important area.

00:36:12.720 --> 00:36:14.020
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II:
That's not relevant today.

00:36:14.020 --> 00:36:15.610
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: I
think it could be.

00:36:15.610 --> 00:36:20.420
Could be. Could be the way that
things get lost even in emails,

00:36:20.420 --> 00:36:22.000
reminds me of the few minutes

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:26.180
of the phone calls
that were also lost.

00:36:26.180 --> 00:36:29.440
So, during the time
that you started at NBC,

00:36:29.440 --> 00:36:31.480
I can remember you
telling me a story

00:36:31.480 --> 00:36:33.610
of some advice that
you'd gotten.

00:36:33.610 --> 00:36:35.840
It started out never
use a hammer

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:38.880
when a screwdriver would do.

00:36:38.880 --> 00:36:42.390
And I just wanted you to
kind of like turn the corner

00:36:42.390 --> 00:36:44.630
on that story and
let us know about how

00:36:44.630 --> 00:36:46.470
that advice really
helped you to get

00:36:46.470 --> 00:36:50.420
through another very
interesting situation at NBC.

00:36:50.420 --> 00:36:52.190
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II: Well,

00:36:52.190 --> 00:36:55.150
getting the job NBC
number one was a miracle.

00:36:55.150 --> 00:36:58.480
Because I ended up going
to the interview directly

00:36:58.480 --> 00:37:02.290
from the Jefferson
Building on my lunch break.

00:37:02.290 --> 00:37:07.430
And I was tipped by a young lady
up there named Easter Winters

00:37:07.430 --> 00:37:13.400
who is the chief engineer's
executive assistant.

00:37:13.400 --> 00:37:16.120
And she called me at work and
said you know the interview

00:37:16.120 --> 00:37:18.220
that you had set
up for tomorrow,

00:37:18.220 --> 00:37:21.280
by tomorrow all those
jobs will be filled.

00:37:21.280 --> 00:37:22.770
Can you come this afternoon?

00:37:22.770 --> 00:37:27.020
I was like oh, because I didn't
have a suit on like I have

00:37:27.020 --> 00:37:29.320
on now, I had on a nice dashiki.

00:37:29.320 --> 00:37:32.190
You young people Google that.

00:37:32.190 --> 00:37:35.360
You can see what I'm
talking about, you know.

00:37:35.360 --> 00:37:38.350
So, here I am going to
the most conservative

00:37:38.350 --> 00:37:40.700
of the then three networks,

00:37:40.700 --> 00:37:44.510
if you can imagine
that in a dashiki.

00:37:44.510 --> 00:37:46.060
I didn't like my chances.

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:48.370
And I told Easter, well, maybe.

00:37:48.370 --> 00:37:49.670
She said, no, no, no.

00:37:49.670 --> 00:37:53.180
If you come tomorrow it will be
a purely ceremonial interview.

00:37:53.180 --> 00:37:55.670
Today is the thing.

00:37:55.670 --> 00:37:58.950
Went up there, met a
gentleman name Mr. Kirkham,

00:37:58.950 --> 00:38:00.250
chit chat, chit chat, chit chat.

00:38:00.250 --> 00:38:03.660
I tried to just blind him with
my personality and good looks,

00:38:03.660 --> 00:38:05.480
so he wouldn't see the
shirt I was wearing.

00:38:05.480 --> 00:38:09.750
You know? And you know, told
him all the things I had done,

00:38:09.750 --> 00:38:12.430
the Library of Congress, WAMUFM.

00:38:12.430 --> 00:38:15.170
I did not have a first class
FCC license, which is one

00:38:15.170 --> 00:38:16.610
of the things he wanted.

00:38:16.610 --> 00:38:19.120
And we had a good interview,
but now we're on our way

00:38:19.120 --> 00:38:21.930
out the door, we're about
to get to the corridor

00:38:21.930 --> 00:38:24.750
and I haven't closed the deal.

00:38:24.750 --> 00:38:27.670
And just before he gave me
that last little shove back

00:38:27.670 --> 00:38:28.990
into the hallway, I
said, oh yeah and how's

00:38:28.990 --> 00:38:31.590
that new PCP 90 working out,

00:38:31.590 --> 00:38:36.570
which was the then brand new
minicam that RCA had created,

00:38:36.570 --> 00:38:39.300
he says, you know
about the PCP 90?

00:38:39.300 --> 00:38:41.450
I said yeah, absolutely,
it sounds like,

00:38:41.450 --> 00:38:44.760
and this is where I use my
American University education.

00:38:44.760 --> 00:38:46.210
I said this sounds
like it's going

00:38:46.210 --> 00:38:48.550
to revolutionize
the newsgathering

00:38:48.550 --> 00:38:50.250
business [laughter].

00:38:50.250 --> 00:38:52.930
I was praying that
something was going

00:38:52.930 --> 00:38:54.290
to get through to this guy.

00:38:54.290 --> 00:38:58.810
And he said, okay, he said,
well would you like to see it?

00:38:58.810 --> 00:39:00.560
I said it's here already?

00:39:00.560 --> 00:39:03.540
He takes me back to the shop,
he shows me this camera,

00:39:03.540 --> 00:39:06.780
we're sitting there like,
pardon me, two ladies looking

00:39:06.780 --> 00:39:11.430
through the maternity room
glass at this brand new camera,

00:39:11.430 --> 00:39:13.420
and then he whispers two
words that I'll never forget,

00:39:13.420 --> 00:39:14.720
he said well when can you start?

00:39:14.720 --> 00:39:16.580
I said well, I'll be
back here at 5 o'clock.

00:39:16.580 --> 00:39:19.930
He said, no we'll
call you in two weeks.

00:39:19.930 --> 00:39:23.480
So, cut to the story that
Luis is referring to.

00:39:23.480 --> 00:39:27.650
So, because it's a union shop,
because it's a seniority shop,

00:39:27.650 --> 00:39:31.460
the people that NBC had
at the time in its employ,

00:39:31.460 --> 00:39:34.040
that they couldn't be fired
because of their seniority,

00:39:34.040 --> 00:39:37.800
but they had some
questionable credentials.

00:39:37.800 --> 00:39:43.620
Two or three of these gentlemen
were card carrying clansmen.

00:39:43.620 --> 00:39:46.930
Not rumored to be, actually.

00:39:46.930 --> 00:39:49.160
And one of those
gentlemen was the supervisor

00:39:49.160 --> 00:39:52.340
of projection island, which
is where I was working,

00:39:52.340 --> 00:39:55.370
and you know he did a
fair job of telling me how

00:39:55.370 --> 00:39:57.420
to turn the projector on
and off, how to thread it

00:39:57.420 --> 00:39:58.720
and so forth and so on,

00:39:58.720 --> 00:40:00.430
but he wasn't giving
me any real details.

00:40:00.430 --> 00:40:03.220
And eventually after three weeks
of trying to appeal to his ego

00:40:03.220 --> 00:40:06.090
and other tactics to try to get
him to kind of loosen up on some

00:40:06.090 --> 00:40:08.830
of that information
he had stored up here,

00:40:08.830 --> 00:40:10.590
one of the black
technical directors,

00:40:10.590 --> 00:40:12.070
a gentleman named Carl Bailey,

00:40:12.070 --> 00:40:15.110
I think he was the first
black TV TD in the country.

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:17.130
He said, man you don't have to
worry about him, just go back

00:40:17.130 --> 00:40:18.830
to the maintenance
shop, get the book,

00:40:18.830 --> 00:40:20.130
get the maintenance manual.

00:40:20.130 --> 00:40:21.670
I was like yes.

00:40:21.670 --> 00:40:22.970
And he said, then
you can come back

00:40:22.970 --> 00:40:25.290
on your lunch hour
and you can read.

00:40:25.290 --> 00:40:26.590
I said no.

00:40:26.590 --> 00:40:27.890
He said no?

00:40:27.890 --> 00:40:29.190
I said no, no.

00:40:29.190 --> 00:40:32.070
I'm going to bring that
to my workstations.

00:40:32.070 --> 00:40:33.370
Yeah, okay bring it
to your workstation.

00:40:33.370 --> 00:40:34.980
I said no, but listen
to what I'm saying,

00:40:34.980 --> 00:40:37.160
bring it to my workstation,

00:40:37.160 --> 00:40:39.110
with his orientation
there's no way he's going

00:40:39.110 --> 00:40:41.110
to walk past me seeing
me reading something

00:40:41.110 --> 00:40:43.940
and not come check on
what I'm reading, okay.

00:40:43.940 --> 00:40:46.050
That's the bait.

00:40:46.050 --> 00:40:48.390
And then I took another
piece of my AU education

00:40:48.390 --> 00:40:51.230
and brought my little legal
pad with me and a pen.

00:40:51.230 --> 00:40:52.930
I knew when he was
coming back from lunch.

00:40:52.930 --> 00:40:54.930
I had the book open, I'm
writing my notes down,

00:40:54.930 --> 00:40:57.320
I'm being a very good
college student here.

00:40:57.320 --> 00:41:00.360
And he comes up over my shoulder
and he asked me was I trying

00:41:00.360 --> 00:41:01.660
to get a job in maintenance?

00:41:01.660 --> 00:41:02.960
I said, well no, I
said well, you know,

00:41:02.960 --> 00:41:04.900
here's something you
don't know about me.

00:41:04.900 --> 00:41:06.980
So, I had already set up three

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:10.270
or four code messages
in this reply.

00:41:10.270 --> 00:41:12.140
Number one, my dad's
a master carpenter.

00:41:12.140 --> 00:41:14.790
So, that means he has a
trade, you have a trade.

00:41:14.790 --> 00:41:18.940
The worst whooping, I got from
my dad, I've been disciplined

00:41:18.940 --> 00:41:21.040
and you know what discipline
is, you probably handed out some

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:24.950
of yours yourself, am I write,
was then I used a hammer

00:41:24.950 --> 00:41:28.550
and a screwdriver to do the
job of a hammer and a chisel.

00:41:28.550 --> 00:41:33.140
And my dad said to me, boy,
which code number three, right?

00:41:33.140 --> 00:41:37.280
If you can't use my tools in a
proper manner, don't touch them.

00:41:37.280 --> 00:41:39.800
I make my living with my tools.

00:41:39.800 --> 00:41:41.500
And then I turned to
him and I said sir,

00:41:41.500 --> 00:41:44.200
I said these tools back here
are a lot more expensive,

00:41:44.200 --> 00:41:47.840
I just want to make sure
I know what I'm doing.

00:41:47.840 --> 00:41:50.940
Victory [laugther].

00:41:50.940 --> 00:41:54.380
From that point on he showed
me every screw adjustment,

00:41:54.380 --> 00:41:58.150
every circuit breaker,
every lubrication point,

00:41:58.150 --> 00:42:01.870
how to run the 35-mm projector,
which meant that when he was

00:42:01.870 --> 00:42:04.060
out of the building, I was
the only person who'd do

00:42:04.060 --> 00:42:05.460
"Meet The Press."

00:42:05.460 --> 00:42:08.290
Because at the time, that was
the only national commercial

00:42:08.290 --> 00:42:10.290
that Channel 4 only
national commercial

00:42:10.290 --> 00:42:11.590
that Channel 4 ran locally.

00:42:11.590 --> 00:42:13.740
All the rest of them
would run from New York.

00:42:13.740 --> 00:42:16.710
But you know, I try to mention
that story to folks today,

00:42:16.710 --> 00:42:18.440
because folks that
you don't agree with,

00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:21.410
you don't understand, or
don't agree with there on,

00:42:21.410 --> 00:42:23.720
if that is the door
you have to go through,

00:42:23.720 --> 00:42:25.430
you have to go through
that door.

00:42:25.430 --> 00:42:29.670
So, I said there's got to
be a way I can get this guy

00:42:29.670 --> 00:42:33.520
to understand, I'm not here to
pour molasses in the equipment.

00:42:33.520 --> 00:42:37.830
I'm not here of spray paint
NAACP over that projector.

00:42:37.830 --> 00:42:41.260
I just want to be an NBC
engineer, have a white shirt,

00:42:41.260 --> 00:42:44.390
RCA pocket protector,
little air hose

00:42:44.390 --> 00:42:46.830
to blow the dust
out of the gate.

00:42:46.830 --> 00:42:50.120
And put my 8, or 9, or 12
hours in and collect my check.

00:42:50.120 --> 00:42:53.480
Now, he never invited me over
for dinner, but that was okay.

00:42:53.480 --> 00:42:54.780
That was okay.

00:42:54.780 --> 00:42:58.330
From that summer on,
he basically made sure

00:42:58.330 --> 00:43:02.370
if there was any question about
that shop that I needed to ask,

00:43:02.370 --> 00:43:04.390
come ask him, because he
knew where everything was.

00:43:04.390 --> 00:43:05.690
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: Fantastic.

00:43:05.690 --> 00:43:07.680
I think there is a
huge secret to success

00:43:07.680 --> 00:43:09.070
in what you just told us.

00:43:09.070 --> 00:43:11.110
And your life represents
that for us.

00:43:11.110 --> 00:43:16.300
So, we are honoring you today
and I'm just really reminded

00:43:16.300 --> 00:43:20.120
of that with a story like that.

00:43:20.120 --> 00:43:23.770
Is it okay if we get to
1979 and going to LA?

00:43:23.770 --> 00:43:25.070
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II:
Yeah, let's roll with it.

00:43:25.070 --> 00:43:26.370
Let's roll with it.

00:43:26.370 --> 00:43:29.940
These people are only getting
older out there listening to me.

00:43:29.940 --> 00:43:32.820
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: It's
1979, what's going

00:43:32.820 --> 00:43:37.850
on with what are you thinking

00:43:37.850 --> 00:43:39.150
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams,
II: Well, at that time,

00:43:39.150 --> 00:43:42.810
and this is well before Homeland
Security had come along.

00:43:42.810 --> 00:43:46.030
There were a lot more
feature film shooting in DC,

00:43:46.030 --> 00:43:48.700
at least portions of them, one
of them I remember seeing is

00:43:48.700 --> 00:43:51.240
"Being There" with
Peter Sellers.

00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:54.240
I just saw Peters Sellers
walking down 14th Street

00:43:54.240 --> 00:43:55.540
and some other locations.

00:43:55.540 --> 00:43:59.920
And so, by this time, I had
also worked at Channel 7, local,

00:43:59.920 --> 00:44:03.360
which was shooting news on film.

00:44:03.360 --> 00:44:05.700
And so, that was my first
professional experience working

00:44:05.700 --> 00:44:07.000
with film.

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:08.980
So, I said you know,
maybe it's time to think

00:44:08.980 --> 00:44:13.370
about taking the Neste plunge
and going to Los Angeles to see

00:44:13.370 --> 00:44:19.660
if I could get into
big show business.

00:44:19.660 --> 00:44:23.090
From "Ben Hur," I recognized

00:44:23.090 --> 00:44:25.230
that sometimes you don't
recognize the miracles

00:44:25.230 --> 00:44:27.750
that are right in front of
you, but miracles still exist.

00:44:27.750 --> 00:44:30.980
So, in the same pile of mail
that I got a no thank you

00:44:30.980 --> 00:44:35.090
from AFI, when I applied
to their directing program,

00:44:35.090 --> 00:44:39.470
good old Uncle Sam gave me
a nice income tax return.

00:44:39.470 --> 00:44:42.500
I said, you know what, there's
more than one way to get to LA.

00:44:42.500 --> 00:44:45.620
So, there was this airline
back then, called TWA.

00:44:45.620 --> 00:44:50.760
You all Google it, you
young folks, Google it.

00:44:50.760 --> 00:44:56.250
I had planned to go to LA, and
I took a 90-day leave of absence

00:44:56.250 --> 00:44:58.820
from WMAL radio, which
was my permanent job

00:44:58.820 --> 00:45:00.450
at the time, to try LA.

00:45:00.450 --> 00:45:07.580
I was also headed down the
aisle in September of that year.

00:45:07.580 --> 00:45:11.600
And I had wedding plans already
in place, deposits had been put

00:45:11.600 --> 00:45:13.620
down on a rehearsal hall
or something like that,

00:45:13.620 --> 00:45:16.560
why are you laughing, Sam?

00:45:16.560 --> 00:45:20.020
I'm trying to tell a story over
here and you're interrupting me.

00:45:20.020 --> 00:45:26.200
And as things do happen in
your life from time to time,

00:45:26.200 --> 00:45:29.750
at the time, the betrothed
and I were both going to LA,

00:45:29.750 --> 00:45:32.120
because she was working
here for WETA

00:45:32.120 --> 00:45:34.460
and planned to go to KCET in LA.

00:45:34.460 --> 00:45:37.430
And of course, I was just going
to go to anybody out there

00:45:37.430 --> 00:45:39.190
that would get me a paycheck.

00:45:39.190 --> 00:45:40.900
And then at the last minute

00:45:40.900 --> 00:45:43.450
or she decided she
didn't think she could be

00:45:43.450 --> 00:45:46.820
that far away from her folks.

00:45:46.820 --> 00:45:49.480
So, maybe we could get
married, but then maybe wait

00:45:49.480 --> 00:45:51.270
until the next year
to go out to LA.

00:45:51.270 --> 00:45:56.050
And I was like, I'm certainly
not liking the sound of that.

00:45:56.050 --> 00:45:59.370
Especially since I'm already
unemployed for 90 days.

00:45:59.370 --> 00:46:02.400
There is no going back on that
you know leave of absence,

00:46:02.400 --> 00:46:04.220
they've already hired
somebody else to cover me.

00:46:04.220 --> 00:46:08.430
So, I said well, you know what
think about it, and let me know,

00:46:08.430 --> 00:46:12.810
but I said, my future,
somehow I see LA in my future.

00:46:12.810 --> 00:46:15.530
And so, she didn't move on
her position, so I said,

00:46:15.530 --> 00:46:18.700
well I think we're going to
have to tell your parents,

00:46:18.700 --> 00:46:20.000
we're not getting married.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:21.300
Well, why aren't we getting?

00:46:21.300 --> 00:46:24.650
Well, you want to; I mean
how are we doing this?

00:46:24.650 --> 00:46:27.590
So, as it turned out I
had to go to Baltimore

00:46:27.590 --> 00:46:31.440
in her parents' kitchen and
very wisely tell her parents,

00:46:31.440 --> 00:46:36.720
well I didn't deserve a woman
as wonderful as their daughter.

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:39.410
And I didn't go in and say
that she was just a coward,

00:46:39.410 --> 00:46:41.700
and just didn't want
to take that next step.

00:46:41.700 --> 00:46:43.000
That wouldn't have been smart,

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:45.560
that were so many butcher
knives, and other you know,

00:46:45.560 --> 00:46:47.180
things that could
have been projectiles

00:46:47.180 --> 00:46:48.480
in the room, you know.

00:46:48.480 --> 00:46:51.330
So, we got through that and
we were all cool after that.

00:46:51.330 --> 00:46:53.590
But that's when I realized

00:46:53.590 --> 00:46:57.460
that I was laser
focused on this career.

00:46:57.460 --> 00:47:01.940
And as it turned out,
had I waited a year,

00:47:01.940 --> 00:47:06.140
just so you all can jump
to the next chapter,

00:47:06.140 --> 00:47:09.080
had I waited a year, then
that would have been right

00:47:09.080 --> 00:47:11.990
at the beginning of the
Screen Actors Guild strike,

00:47:11.990 --> 00:47:15.610
which shut Los Angeles
down for months.

00:47:15.610 --> 00:47:17.450
I couldn't have even gotten
arrested, and we're talking

00:47:17.450 --> 00:47:21.370
about LAPD, I couldn't have
even gotten arrested out there.

00:47:21.370 --> 00:47:23.950
So, timing is everything.

00:47:23.950 --> 00:47:26.490
And so, I went at the
right time, it worked out.

00:47:26.490 --> 00:47:28.850
I guess, otherwise,
Luis wouldn't have me

00:47:28.850 --> 00:47:31.990
up here boring you
with all these stories.

00:47:31.990 --> 00:47:34.440
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: Well, I'm glad
you selected your words properly

00:47:34.440 --> 00:47:36.160
for the young lady's family.

00:47:36.160 --> 00:47:37.460
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams,
II: Oh yeah,

00:47:37.460 --> 00:47:38.760
I mean you know I was like,

00:47:38.760 --> 00:47:42.460
oh you know I might need
this neck some other time.

00:47:42.460 --> 00:47:44.690
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: Well,
great you still have it.

00:47:44.690 --> 00:47:49.640
What did a break look like
for you once you were in LA?

00:47:49.640 --> 00:47:52.780
What did that moment look
like when you said, well yeah,

00:47:52.780 --> 00:47:55.070
I'm on the right track now.

00:47:55.070 --> 00:47:58.240
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II: Luis,
that's a loaded question.

00:47:58.240 --> 00:48:01.550
First job off the plane, now
I want to see a show of hands

00:48:01.550 --> 00:48:03.730
and you young people don't
even bother to answer,

00:48:03.730 --> 00:48:05.590
because I know you're
not up to this.

00:48:05.590 --> 00:48:08.960
Who's ever heard
of Rudy Ray Moore?

00:48:08.960 --> 00:48:14.730
Okay, I don't see anybody with
a full head of hear [laughter].

00:48:14.730 --> 00:48:18.420
Okay, Rudy Ray, the actual
first person I worked for in LA

00:48:18.420 --> 00:48:20.610
at the Dunbar Hotel
on Central Avenue

00:48:20.610 --> 00:48:25.440
where he was living
in the basement.

00:48:25.440 --> 00:48:31.460
And just to show you that
I could remain optimistic.

00:48:31.460 --> 00:48:32.760
I mean because he
was a nice cat,

00:48:32.760 --> 00:48:34.690
don't get me wrong,
really nice guy.

00:48:34.690 --> 00:48:41.080
But his jokes were
you know, yeah.

00:48:41.080 --> 00:48:45.070
So, basically when I
realized that I may,

00:48:45.070 --> 00:48:47.400
have I made the right decision,

00:48:47.400 --> 00:48:48.890
one of the first
jokes I recorded

00:48:48.890 --> 00:48:52.690
that he said was how do you keep
the flies out of your kitchen?

00:48:52.690 --> 00:48:58.670
Well, it's real simple,
you keep the bucket

00:48:58.670 --> 00:49:00.850
of in the living room.

00:49:00.850 --> 00:49:05.720
And so, immediately
I started [laughter].

00:49:08.240 --> 00:49:10.930
You know, and one
of my assistants was

00:49:10.930 --> 00:49:12.230
like what are you doing?

00:49:12.230 --> 00:49:13.530
I said, well I'm just trying

00:49:13.530 --> 00:49:14.830
to make sure this is
the actual bottom.

00:49:14.830 --> 00:49:17.550
That there's no other
level below this,

00:49:17.550 --> 00:49:21.060
so I can only go up from here.

00:49:21.060 --> 00:49:23.550
So, that was the
actual first job.

00:49:23.550 --> 00:49:26.230
And then, if you got a job,
it was three or four days

00:49:26.230 --> 00:49:28.250
in a row, okay that's great.

00:49:28.250 --> 00:49:30.360
Two weeks in a row,
okay that's great.

00:49:30.360 --> 00:49:33.970
It took me seven years to get
into the labor union out there,

00:49:33.970 --> 00:49:36.880
which is not the same
issue as it would be today,

00:49:36.880 --> 00:49:38.850
because the rules have changed.

00:49:38.850 --> 00:49:41.030
And I worked for a lot
of different people,

00:49:41.030 --> 00:49:43.840
a lot of low-budget
producers and directors.

00:49:43.840 --> 00:49:47.460
I would say one of the
first big brakes I got was

00:49:47.460 --> 00:49:49.950
through a director
named Alan Meyerson

00:49:49.950 --> 00:49:52.190
who I had worked
another 2 or 3 days,

00:49:52.190 --> 00:49:55.770
22 hour days for flat $100.

00:49:55.770 --> 00:49:57.920
And like a lot of people out
there will tell you, kid,

00:49:57.920 --> 00:49:59.220
you know when I get
some real money,

00:49:59.220 --> 00:50:00.520
I'm going to call
you again, you know.

00:50:00.520 --> 00:50:01.820
How many times, if
you had a quarter

00:50:01.820 --> 00:50:05.070
for every time somebody told
you that, you'd be staring

00:50:05.070 --> 00:50:07.420
down at Bill Gates saying, see?

00:50:07.420 --> 00:50:10.490
See? But he did call.

00:50:10.490 --> 00:50:12.990
And that job turned
out to be five months

00:50:12.990 --> 00:50:15.390
of work, and I was like ah.

00:50:15.390 --> 00:50:18.070
I bought a new van,
bought a lot of new gear.

00:50:18.070 --> 00:50:20.800
You know, I was respectable all
of the sudden, I started looking

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:24.490
at housing prices, you know.

00:50:24.490 --> 00:50:27.450
But it's really one job at
a time, and it's really,

00:50:27.450 --> 00:50:31.190
my first three years were more
like, they weren't calling me.

00:50:31.190 --> 00:50:33.540
They were calling the
person that they knew,

00:50:33.540 --> 00:50:35.690
and the person they knew
may have been busy and said,

00:50:35.690 --> 00:50:36.990
you know what there's
this new kid

00:50:36.990 --> 00:50:39.950
out here named Russell Williams,
he'll do a good job for you.

00:50:39.950 --> 00:50:41.370
Give him a shot.

00:50:41.370 --> 00:50:43.710
So, it was three years before
anybody was actually calling

00:50:43.710 --> 00:50:45.010
me directly.

00:50:45.010 --> 00:50:48.340
They were calling Luis,
because they already knew Luis.

00:50:48.340 --> 00:50:53.290
And you have to understand
regardless of gender, age,

00:50:53.290 --> 00:50:57.420
religious preference,
ethnicity, the scariest thing

00:50:57.420 --> 00:51:00.320
in a highly competitive
field is someone

00:51:00.320 --> 00:51:03.430
who is an unknown quantity.

00:51:03.430 --> 00:51:06.210
And once you find a team
that works together well,

00:51:06.210 --> 00:51:09.440
you probably, you know the
whole Yankees that we all hated

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:11.730
when we were outside
of New York,

00:51:11.730 --> 00:51:13.690
the reason that they
stayed the old Yankees

00:51:13.690 --> 00:51:16.390
because they very rarely
took on any new talent.

00:51:16.390 --> 00:51:20.000
Because they had Murderers'
Row and all those other folks.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:23.060
