So, she saw the hashtag.

00:59:02.630 --> 00:59:04.820
She heard the outcry.

00:59:04.820 --> 00:59:12.140
But let's talk about why the
Academy looks like it does.

00:59:12.140 --> 00:59:14.090
First of all, the
film business started

00:59:14.090 --> 00:59:16.610
in the Jim Crow era
in the United States.

00:59:16.610 --> 00:59:21.170
So, it was very difficult for
anybody with a permanent tan

00:59:21.170 --> 00:59:25.400
to get on the set to
build a career long enough

00:59:25.400 --> 00:59:28.180
that you could be
invited or be nominated

00:59:28.180 --> 00:59:29.670
for one of the two statues.

00:59:29.670 --> 00:59:32.160
There's only two ways
to get into the Academy,

00:59:32.160 --> 00:59:35.730
that have to be nominated
for an Oscar, or two people

00:59:35.730 --> 00:59:39.580
in the branch that you're
representing, be it camera,

00:59:39.580 --> 00:59:42.460
sound, costume, acting,
directing.

00:59:42.460 --> 00:59:46.430
Two people from those branches
have to send a letter saying,

00:59:46.430 --> 00:59:47.730
you know what, we want

00:59:47.730 --> 00:59:50.290
to consider Roselyn
Williams as a new member.

00:59:50.290 --> 00:59:52.620
And the membership
committee of that branch.

00:59:52.620 --> 00:59:54.510
There's 17 branches.

00:59:54.510 --> 00:59:57.720
Each one of those branches
has a different set of rules.

00:59:57.720 --> 01:00:03.850
So, imagine my surprise on,
I think it was March 26th,

01:00:03.850 --> 01:00:09.880
of 1990 that not only was I
nominated and won the Oscar,

01:00:09.880 --> 01:00:12.920
but then they said, but I'm
not automatically invited

01:00:12.920 --> 01:00:16.100
into the Academy yet.

01:00:16.100 --> 01:00:21.180
And that's when, southeast
DC came out of my mouth,

01:00:21.180 --> 01:00:22.480
and I said now wait a minute is

01:00:22.480 --> 01:00:24.560
that the black rule,
or is that the rule?

01:00:24.560 --> 01:00:26.970
And they said, no, no,
no it's in the rule book.

01:00:26.970 --> 01:00:28.270
And I said what's
the rule book say.

01:00:28.270 --> 01:00:31.990
So, in other words, you
needed 8 years of credits

01:00:31.990 --> 01:00:33.690
to be considered,
in addition to,

01:00:33.690 --> 01:00:35.900
and that's still
on the rule book.

01:00:35.900 --> 01:00:41.120
So, sound, for some reason
has the longest requirement

01:00:41.120 --> 01:00:44.140
of experience of any
of the other branches.

01:00:44.140 --> 01:00:46.330
If you're in the acting
branch, just the fact

01:00:46.330 --> 01:00:47.630
that you got nominated,

01:00:47.630 --> 01:00:50.130
generally is enough
to get an invite.

01:00:50.130 --> 01:00:51.430
So, that's one.

01:00:51.430 --> 01:00:53.430
But now, let's put this
in the realm of sports,

01:00:53.430 --> 01:00:56.410
because I think it's a lot
easier for people to understand

01:00:56.410 --> 01:01:00.880
that the Academies, plural,
meaning Music Academy,

01:01:00.880 --> 01:01:03.010
Television Academy,
Motion Picture Academy,

01:01:03.010 --> 01:01:06.360
what they really do
is keep people out.

01:01:06.360 --> 01:01:07.990
That's what they really do.

01:01:07.990 --> 01:01:11.930
Okay, the same way the Hall of
Fame doesn't accept everybody,

01:01:11.930 --> 01:01:14.800
be it football, or baseball,
who's played the sport.

01:01:14.800 --> 01:01:17.720
Okay, even someone
like Karl Malone

01:01:17.720 --> 01:01:21.600
who had 18 great seasons playing
basketball, he never got a ring.

01:01:21.600 --> 01:01:23.510
But we can accept
that in sports.

01:01:23.510 --> 01:01:26.650
Because, one, we know the score,
we know all the statistics.

01:01:26.650 --> 01:01:31.540
And most of that
process is transparent.

01:01:31.540 --> 01:01:33.910
We don't really see
the Academy's process.

01:01:33.910 --> 01:01:35.900
I don't know whether
"Glory" won by 1 vote,

01:01:35.900 --> 01:01:37.940
or 10 votes, or 1000 votes.

01:01:37.940 --> 01:01:41.330
So, I'm fairly sure that
process will remain opaque,

01:01:41.330 --> 01:01:42.630
and so people don't trust it

01:01:42.630 --> 01:01:43.930
because they don't
know what's going on,

01:01:43.930 --> 01:01:46.210
if anything, behind the scenes.

01:01:46.210 --> 01:01:51.770
I would also say that the whole
concept of it being difficult

01:01:51.770 --> 01:01:55.330
to win an Oscar, Emmy or
Grammy is going to remain.

01:01:55.330 --> 01:01:58.170
You know, they're not handing
them out at Home Depot,

01:01:58.170 --> 01:02:01.300
or at Starbuck's when you
get that extra tall latte.

01:02:01.300 --> 01:02:04.820
It's supposed to be a
hurdle that you jump over.

01:02:04.820 --> 01:02:07.720
So, that makes people upset
because they're thinking,

01:02:07.720 --> 01:02:13.340
well how did this film not get
recognized, da, da, da, da, da.

01:02:13.340 --> 01:02:16.810
It's a lot of that is math.

01:02:16.810 --> 01:02:20.670
Okay. If there were 350
or so movies this year

01:02:20.670 --> 01:02:24.060
that were eligible for Oscar
nomination, let's say each one

01:02:24.060 --> 01:02:28.080
of those movies had at
least 10 actors in it, okay.

01:02:28.080 --> 01:02:29.900
And of course some of
these actors appear in more

01:02:29.900 --> 01:02:31.770
than one movie per year,
but you're talking more

01:02:31.770 --> 01:02:35.680
than 3000 roles, which
have to be whittled

01:02:35.680 --> 01:02:38.300
down to only 20 nominations.

01:02:38.300 --> 01:02:41.090
So, best, best, and
supporting, supporting.

01:02:41.090 --> 01:02:43.390
So, it's almost as
bad as thinking

01:02:43.390 --> 01:02:46.820
that Powerball is a
sure thing [laughter].

01:02:46.820 --> 01:02:52.640
Okay, and I can think of
a lot of actors that are

01:02:52.640 --> 01:02:56.190
in the so-called tribe
that didn't win Oscars.

01:02:56.190 --> 01:02:59.270
Directors like Hitchcock
never won an Oscar.

01:02:59.270 --> 01:03:00.570
You know what I'm saying.

01:03:00.570 --> 01:03:02.690
So, a lot of times,
we may look at it

01:03:02.690 --> 01:03:05.820
as this is directed
towards people of color,

01:03:05.820 --> 01:03:09.510
but what it really is, is that
mathematically it's difficult,

01:03:09.510 --> 01:03:13.620
and then, because of the way the
membership looked at the time,

01:03:13.620 --> 01:03:16.650
maybe it was going to be
more difficult for you

01:03:16.650 --> 01:03:20.020
to determine whether, say
Don Cheadle's role in "Devil

01:03:20.020 --> 01:03:22.890
In a Blue Dress" was
him in character,

01:03:22.890 --> 01:03:25.240
or that was just Don Cheadle.

01:03:25.240 --> 01:03:28.390
See, now we know Don Cheadle's
got a whole lot of range.

01:03:28.390 --> 01:03:29.690
But at the time, you know,

01:03:29.690 --> 01:03:31.040
I think some people
were kind of befuddled.

01:03:31.040 --> 01:03:34.090
Is that kid really that
good, or is that just him?

01:03:34.090 --> 01:03:38.510
So, with the real push to
diversify, and also add a lot

01:03:38.510 --> 01:03:41.700
of younger members,
the Academy is hoping

01:03:41.700 --> 01:03:46.320
that the representation
in the nomination

01:03:46.320 --> 01:03:49.020
which has been fairly good
this year will continue

01:03:49.020 --> 01:03:51.070
to go in that direction.

01:03:51.070 --> 01:03:56.880
But say, in my branch, I can
say with almost 100% surety,

01:03:56.880 --> 01:04:00.910
there are only five African
Americans in the sound branch,

01:04:00.910 --> 01:04:05.020
and maybe 6 people
of Hispanic descent,

01:04:05.020 --> 01:04:08.720
of a branch that's
about 450 people.

01:04:08.720 --> 01:04:15.530
Okay, so part of that
is that what do we want

01:04:15.530 --> 01:04:16.830
to do in the business.

01:04:16.830 --> 01:04:22.730
Do we want to do sound, or do we
want to act, direct, you know?

01:04:22.730 --> 01:04:25.880
So, if no one is pursuing
a career in sound,

01:04:25.880 --> 01:04:29.250
then that can't be
blamed on the Academy.

01:04:29.250 --> 01:04:30.750
If I wanted to blame somebody,

01:04:30.750 --> 01:04:32.940
I might maybe drop
the Image Awards,

01:04:32.940 --> 01:04:37.390
because the Image Awards very
rarely highlights people's

01:04:37.390 --> 01:04:42.650
accomplishments behind camera,
so that kids like me trying

01:04:42.650 --> 01:04:45.410
to figure out what to do in
showbusiness would know, oh,

01:04:45.410 --> 01:04:46.890
wow, I could be a
cinematographer.

01:04:46.890 --> 01:04:49.510
Okay, because you know, nobody's
going to hire me as an actor.

01:04:49.510 --> 01:04:51.310
Or, oh, maybe I could be
a production designer.

01:04:51.310 --> 01:04:53.570
Or maybe I could
do visual effects.

01:04:53.570 --> 01:04:55.280
And the only reason that I ended

01:04:55.280 --> 01:04:59.050
up even considering African
Americans working behind camera,

01:04:59.050 --> 01:05:02.470
was because in 1967 when
I went to see "In the Heat

01:05:02.470 --> 01:05:05.990
of the Night" on the big screen
for the sixth or seventh time,

01:05:05.990 --> 01:05:07.290
I said wait a minute,
wait a minute,

01:05:07.290 --> 01:05:10.320
I said Quincy Jones
did the score.

01:05:10.320 --> 01:05:12.070
I said, so what the African
Americans are working

01:05:12.070 --> 01:05:13.370
behind camera?

01:05:13.370 --> 01:05:15.110
Now, in front of the
camera, that was no headline,

01:05:15.110 --> 01:05:17.620
we had been there
since the silence.

01:05:17.620 --> 01:05:20.490
But, behind camera in an
important role like that,

01:05:20.490 --> 01:05:21.940
I said okay, note to self.

01:05:21.940 --> 01:05:23.240
Now, it didn't mean

01:05:23.240 --> 01:05:26.720
that I immediately started
packing my bags, you know in '67

01:05:26.720 --> 01:05:28.430
and started working towards LA.

01:05:28.430 --> 01:05:30.420
But, at least I knew
the seed was there,

01:05:30.420 --> 01:05:32.080
I knew it was possible.

01:05:32.080 --> 01:05:35.960
And so, when I did get a
chance to shake Quincy's hand,

01:05:35.960 --> 01:05:38.170
many years later I
told him I blamed him,

01:05:38.170 --> 01:05:39.690
I said you're the
reason I'm out here.

01:05:39.690 --> 01:05:41.430
I just want you to know that.

01:05:41.430 --> 01:05:45.300
You're the reason I even
put that up, you know,

01:05:45.300 --> 01:05:46.600
that thought in the air.

01:05:46.600 --> 01:05:50.640
So, that I think is a little
bit about the Academy.

01:05:50.640 --> 01:05:55.570
But you all are free
to try your hand at it.

01:05:55.570 --> 01:05:58.020
I'll help you with
your acceptance speech.

01:05:58.020 --> 01:06:02.420
And I'll point you to people in
your field who can mentor you,

01:06:02.420 --> 01:06:04.300
because that's very important.

01:06:04.300 --> 01:06:05.600
And you can go on
and get your own.

01:06:05.600 --> 01:06:08.550
Because I'm tired of being only
one of three African Americans

01:06:08.550 --> 01:06:09.850
that have multiple Oscars.

01:06:09.850 --> 01:06:11.740
We need a whole lot more folks
in that crowd [applause].

01:06:11.740 --> 01:06:16.740
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell:
Absolutely, well said, sir.

01:06:16.740 --> 01:06:20.200
I know that we're kind
of rounding the corner

01:06:20.200 --> 01:06:22.960
on our time together, but I know

01:06:22.960 --> 01:06:26.090
that some nominees
came out last night.

01:06:26.090 --> 01:06:30.040
"Shape of Water," and "Get
Out" which one is going to win?

01:06:30.040 --> 01:06:33.910
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II:
Oh, for best picture?

01:06:35.670 --> 01:06:40.140
I'm fairly, fairly confident
that "Shape of Water"

01:06:40.140 --> 01:06:46.770
because not that "Get
Out" isn't an impressive,

01:06:46.770 --> 01:06:48.170
not only directorial debut,

01:06:48.170 --> 01:06:51.210
but it just changed the whole
conversation in the room.

01:06:51.210 --> 01:06:59.340
But I want to say that
"Shape of Water" I think,

01:06:59.340 --> 01:07:01.480
by and large is the
kind of movie

01:07:01.480 --> 01:07:05.430
that has Oscar bait
written all over it okay.

01:07:05.430 --> 01:07:07.560
One movie for sure
that I was disappointed

01:07:07.560 --> 01:07:11.590
that did not hit the best
picture nine, because we have

01:07:11.590 --> 01:07:13.640
up to 10, and I said so what
happened with that tenth one?

01:07:13.640 --> 01:07:15.380
It could have been "Mudbound"

01:07:15.380 --> 01:07:18.180
which I thought was very
well directed, very nuance.

01:07:18.180 --> 01:07:19.480
Beautifully shot.

01:07:19.480 --> 01:07:22.500
The first woman to ever be
nominated for cinematography.

01:07:22.500 --> 01:07:24.350
After all these years,

01:07:24.350 --> 01:07:27.100
I mean the first woman I met
doing cinematography I met here

01:07:27.100 --> 01:07:30.370
in DC in '78, was a lady
named Karen Grossman

01:07:30.370 --> 01:07:31.820
who was here in town from LA.

01:07:31.820 --> 01:07:35.680
And I'm thinking, you know.

01:07:35.680 --> 01:07:40.580
But, Dee Rees, who directed
"Mudbound" also got nominated,

01:07:40.580 --> 01:07:45.160
I want to say for adaptive
screenplay, co-nominee.

01:07:45.160 --> 01:07:47.830
"Get Out" I think
is going to do well.

01:07:47.830 --> 01:07:50.910
but I'm kind of thinking
at this moment,

01:07:50.910 --> 01:07:54.630
"The Shape of Water" is going
to be the film this year

01:07:54.630 --> 01:07:55.930
in terms of best picture.

01:07:55.930 --> 01:07:58.070
And that's one thing I wanted
to mention before we move

01:07:58.070 --> 01:08:02.020
on to the Q&amp;A is
that in the branch,

01:08:02.020 --> 01:08:05.110
I can only nominate in sound.

01:08:05.110 --> 01:08:06.890
If my wife was in
directing branch,

01:08:06.890 --> 01:08:08.540
she could only nominate
for directors.

01:08:08.540 --> 01:08:11.050
If my cousin, here, was in the
production designer's branch,

01:08:11.050 --> 01:08:13.310
she could only nominate
for production design.

01:08:13.310 --> 01:08:16.490
But then, we all get to
nominate for best picture.

01:08:16.490 --> 01:08:18.820
So, that's why best
picture nomination is really

01:08:18.820 --> 01:08:22.020
to me more representative
of the actual academy

01:08:22.020 --> 01:08:24.590
than the actual branch
nominations, which could be kind

01:08:24.590 --> 01:08:26.910
of more insider trading.

01:08:26.910 --> 01:08:28.770
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: Well,
thank you very much,

01:08:28.770 --> 01:08:30.720
Professor Russell Williams, II.

01:08:30.720 --> 01:08:35.510
I'd like to thank you on
behalf of everyone here,

01:08:35.510 --> 01:08:39.470
Danial AP Murray African
American Historical Association,

01:08:39.470 --> 01:08:42.450
all of the library
employees that have benefited

01:08:42.450 --> 01:08:44.440
from you being here so early.

01:08:44.440 --> 01:08:45.780
People like me can now walk

01:08:45.780 --> 01:08:49.230
through the halls
quite confidently.

01:08:49.230 --> 01:08:54.860
I also would like to ask
you, what's next for you?

01:08:54.860 --> 01:09:00.340
And then we'll open it up for
the questions and answers.

01:09:00.340 --> 01:09:01.700
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II: Well,
let's see, I've been teaching

01:09:01.700 --> 01:09:03.910
at American for 15 years.

01:09:03.910 --> 01:09:07.380
And I really have enjoyed trying

01:09:07.380 --> 01:09:09.460
to mentor some of
the new talent.

01:09:09.460 --> 01:09:12.390
I have some AU students and
former students in the room,

01:09:12.390 --> 01:09:14.510
could I see some hands.

01:09:14.510 --> 01:09:16.510
Oh, baby.

01:09:16.510 --> 01:09:21.130
[ Applause ]

01:09:21.130 --> 01:09:22.850
Now, not all of these students

01:09:22.850 --> 01:09:25.950
in the room got A's
from me [laughter].

01:09:25.950 --> 01:09:30.550
But the fact that they
understood that I was saying,

01:09:30.550 --> 01:09:33.200
okay bring your game
up a little bit more,

01:09:33.200 --> 01:09:35.160
I'll make that phone
call for you,

01:09:35.160 --> 01:09:38.250
means that I hopefully
did something right.

01:09:38.250 --> 01:09:43.160
I'm still very much
interested in big show business.

01:09:43.160 --> 01:09:45.040
So, anything above the line now.

01:09:45.040 --> 01:09:46.340
Above the line, below the line.

01:09:46.340 --> 01:09:48.760
Below the line means
the creative labor.

01:09:48.760 --> 01:09:50.610
Sound, camera, wardrobe,
makeup and hair.

01:09:50.610 --> 01:09:53.190
But above the line is
writing, producing, directing,

01:09:53.190 --> 01:09:55.940
and sometimes your
top-flight cast.

01:09:55.940 --> 01:09:58.480
I'm always looking
for opportunities

01:09:58.480 --> 01:10:00.930
and things in that realm.

01:10:00.930 --> 01:10:02.230
You know?

01:10:02.230 --> 01:10:04.690
My wife and I want to have
a house in the Vineyard,

01:10:04.690 --> 01:10:07.620
we want to have another
house in Palm Desert.

01:10:07.620 --> 01:10:12.320
So, it may be hard to accomplish
that on an academician salary.

01:10:12.320 --> 01:10:16.180
But, I'm always looking
for opportunities

01:10:16.180 --> 01:10:20.630
to bring the younger generation
in and turn them loose.

01:10:20.630 --> 01:10:24.690
But I can only do that
if they understand naval

01:10:24.690 --> 01:10:26.430
observatory time.

01:10:26.430 --> 01:10:29.050
That's lesson number one.

01:10:29.050 --> 01:10:30.350
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

01:10:30.350 --> 01:10:31.650
Thank you.

01:10:31.650 --> 01:10:32.950
&gt;&gt; Luis Clavell: Absolutely,
well thank you very much, sir.

01:10:32.950 --> 01:10:34.250
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams,
II: Thank you, Luis.

01:10:34.250 --> 01:10:37.490
Ladies and gentlemen, the 2018
Trailblazer Legend Award winner.

01:10:37.490 --> 01:10:41.510
Professor Russel Williams, II.

01:10:41.510 --> 01:10:52.650
[ Applause ]

01:10:52.650 --> 01:10:56.760
&gt;&gt; Darren Jones: Good afternoon,
everybody, I'm Darren Jones,

01:10:56.760 --> 01:10:59.480
the program director for
the Murray Association.

01:10:59.480 --> 01:11:01.640
In the interest of time,
we're going to be able

01:11:01.640 --> 01:11:04.890
to take two questions,
because we don't often,

01:11:04.890 --> 01:11:08.590
in fact we've never had a
two-time Academy award winner

01:11:08.590 --> 01:11:11.790
accept our invitation
and come here.

01:11:11.790 --> 01:11:13.840
And we are on a time schedule.

01:11:13.840 --> 01:11:17.320
We want all of you, if you have
an opportunity to grab a bad

01:11:17.320 --> 01:11:19.730
in the back as you leave
out, but we also want you

01:11:19.730 --> 01:11:24.510
to take a picture with Mr.
Williams, if you so choose.

01:11:24.510 --> 01:11:27.050
So, if there are any questions,
we're going to be able

01:11:27.050 --> 01:11:28.450
to take two, and then
we're going to move

01:11:28.450 --> 01:11:30.780
on to our award presentation.

01:11:30.780 --> 01:11:35.790
Right here in the front.

01:11:35.790 --> 01:11:37.090
&gt;&gt; Melvin Whitten:
Great think you so much,

01:11:37.090 --> 01:11:39.430
my name I Melvin Whitten,
I'm an entertainment lawyer

01:11:39.430 --> 01:11:42.040
and we're really good friends,
but what I wanted to ask you was

01:11:42.040 --> 01:11:45.060
at Howard University
School of Law we had a motto

01:11:45.060 --> 01:11:47.160
that was called lifting
as we climb.

01:11:47.160 --> 01:11:50.380
So, as you climb, you know,
how do you lift and reach back

01:11:50.380 --> 01:11:52.400
and bring others forward.

01:11:52.400 --> 01:11:53.720
&gt;&gt; Russell Williams, II:
Thank you, Mel, good question.

01:11:53.720 --> 01:11:58.970
At our spirits known and unknown
workshop which started in 1971,

01:11:58.970 --> 01:12:02.650
our motto was each
one teach one.

01:12:02.650 --> 01:12:06.600
And that motto has served
me well, my cofounder,

01:12:06.600 --> 01:12:09.690
Gerald Bruce Lee and hopefully
all the people who have come

01:12:09.690 --> 01:12:10.990
through that workshop.

01:12:10.990 --> 01:12:14.170
And even when I was working
in the industry, you know,

01:12:14.170 --> 01:12:17.070
I would look for people who were
interested in what I was doing

01:12:17.070 --> 01:12:20.690
or if they weren't interested in
what I was doing specifically,

01:12:20.690 --> 01:12:23.600
to point them to the
people that can mentor them.

01:12:23.600 --> 01:12:27.180
But at the same time, I
was also vetting them.

01:12:27.180 --> 01:12:28.960
You know, something
like Sergeant Waters

01:12:28.960 --> 01:12:32.120
and "A Soldier's Story" it's
like okay, we're not looking

01:12:32.120 --> 01:12:33.420
for a bunch of fooli9shness,

01:12:33.420 --> 01:12:36.810
because it's image
is everything.

01:12:36.810 --> 01:12:39.520
All right, and especially in
the time I started working

01:12:39.520 --> 01:12:42.470
in the business, I had a couple
directors say, man, you know,

01:12:42.470 --> 01:12:43.870
he said your crew's all black.

01:12:43.870 --> 01:12:45.170
I said yeah.

01:12:45.170 --> 01:12:46.470
He said, well that's
kind of unusual isn't it?

01:12:46.470 --> 01:12:48.750
I said, well, I thought my crew
should reflect the department

01:12:48.750 --> 01:12:50.360
head like everybody else's crew.

01:12:50.360 --> 01:12:53.050
And he said, oh yeah,
yeah, you know [laugther].

01:12:53.050 --> 01:12:55.950
You know what I'm saying.

01:12:55.950 --> 01:12:59.940
So, I mean you have to try
to give them a little truth

01:12:59.940 --> 01:13:02.340
and not make it assaulty.

01:13:02.340 --> 01:13:05.580
But you know to me, Mel,
it's always been important,

01:13:05.580 --> 01:13:08.270
because trust me,
there's no way that I'm

01:13:08.270 --> 01:13:11.310
on this stage telling
my story except

01:13:11.310 --> 01:13:13.890
for people giving
me the opportunity

01:13:13.890 --> 01:13:15.190
to come through the door.

01:13:15.190 --> 01:13:17.920
And people taking a
chance on me Paul Kirkham,

01:13:17.920 --> 01:13:20.460
Paul Fime who was at ABC.

01:13:20.460 --> 01:13:22.620
This guy named Bill Cooper
took me under his wing

01:13:22.620 --> 01:13:23.920
when I came out to LA.

01:13:23.920 --> 01:13:25.580
And that's another thing,

01:13:25.580 --> 01:13:27.480
if you haven't figured
this out already.

01:13:27.480 --> 01:13:30.330
All your mentors may
not look just like you.

01:13:30.330 --> 01:13:34.110
Okay, but if someone's
willing to take the time

01:13:34.110 --> 01:13:36.880
to show you what
made them successful,

01:13:36.880 --> 01:13:40.870
or even if they were an abject
failure, show you how not to go

01:13:40.870 --> 01:13:43.060
down the road that they went
down, which is very important.

01:13:43.060 --> 01:13:45.300
If I see another
movie of someone going

01:13:45.300 --> 01:13:49.850
through the do not
enter bridge out,

01:13:49.850 --> 01:13:52.030
went over the bridge,
went over the cliff.

01:13:52.030 --> 01:13:53.650
Crash the car, then
they crawl back

01:13:53.650 --> 01:13:55.720
up on their fingernails
to the road.

01:13:55.720 --> 01:13:58.680
It's like no, no can't we have
a movie where it shows you how

01:13:58.680 --> 01:14:03.300
to recognize the signs
before you go over the cliff.

01:14:03.300 --> 01:14:04.810
That's the movies I want to see.

01:14:04.810 --> 01:14:06.410
Next question.

01:14:06.410 --> 01:14:08.300
&gt;&gt; Yeah, this is a
pretty quick question.

01:14:08.300 --> 01:14:11.780
Russell and I go back many,
many years and a third friend

01:14:11.780 --> 01:14:13.980
who goes back with us as well.

01:14:13.980 --> 01:14:17.390
I started a production company
some years ago and picked

01:14:17.390 --> 01:14:20.470
up the phone and called the two
of them and they got on a plane,

01:14:20.470 --> 01:14:23.690
and we did the 25th
year anniversary

01:14:23.690 --> 01:14:26.310
of the Congressional
Black Caucus.

01:14:26.310 --> 01:14:31.650
From Bill Cosby to Gladys Knight
and whoever else were all in it.

01:14:31.650 --> 01:14:35.740
And I only had the
nerve to take savings

01:14:35.740 --> 01:14:37.890
and buy cameras and equipment.

01:14:37.890 --> 01:14:40.800
They had the nerve to trust
in me and come to do that.

01:14:40.800 --> 01:14:45.600
So, this is a lesson to all of
you students that are in here.

01:14:45.600 --> 01:14:48.770
I was a student in
that business.

01:14:48.770 --> 01:14:51.530
And this man, really
made a difference for me.

01:14:51.530 --> 01:14:54.980
So, I've actually had a
company, and then sold one.

01:14:54.980 --> 01:14:59.240
So, I'm only saying that to
you, to let you really realize

01:14:59.240 --> 01:15:03.130
that maybe you didn't get an
A in the class [laughter].

01:15:03.130 --> 01:15:05.840
I did. Follow the lead.

01:15:05.840 --> 01:15:09.070
He's there for you.

